    <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
      <p>Martin Ralph DeHaan (commonly know as M. R. DeHaan) was born in Zeeland, Michigan in 1891.  He was raised in the Reformed Church of America and attended Hope College for a year before transferring to the University of Illinois, Chicago to study medicine. He eventually set up a family practice in western Michigan.  A personal medical emergency in 1921 led to a conversion experience that led DeHaan to sell his practice and enroll at Western Theological Seminary.  There he became a convert to dispensational premillenialism and an opponent of infant baptism.</p>
      <p>DeHaan lead a parish in Grand Rapids for nine years.  His often contentious tenure ended when he resigned after suffering a heart attack in 1938.  He then taught evening bible classes, and at the urging  of his mentor William McCarrell, began broadcasting his classes on a small Detroit radio station.  In 1941 the Mutual Network began carrying his radio Bible Class.  After DeHaan suffered a second heart attack while on the air in 1946, and his son Richard assumed more and more responsibility for the broadcast and management of DeHaan's organization.</p>
      <p>DeHaan authored twenty-five books and his organization, Radio Bible Class, of Grand Rapids continued to publish a daily devotional booklet <title render="italic">Our Daily Bread</title>.</p>
      <p>DeHaan died in 1965.</p>
      <p>Sources:  <title render="italic">Encyclopedia of Evangelicalism</title>.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
      <p>The M. R. DeHaan collection consist of  printed copies of sermons delivered by DeHaan.</p>
